{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01TKytcbeycYppvnJi3xQ1tf","type":"tool_result","content":"1\tapiVersion: template.openshift.io/v1\n2\tkind: Template\n3\tmetadata:\n4\t  name: generic-kubelet-config\n5\tobjects:\n6\t  - kind: KubeletConfig\n7\t    apiVersion: machineconfiguration.openshift.io/v1\n8\t    metadata:\n9\t      name: \"${NAME}\"\n10\t    spec:\n11\t      machineConfigPoolSelector:\n12\t        matchLabels:\n13\t          pools.operator.machineconfiguration.openshift.io/${POOL}: ''\n14\t      kubeletConfig: ${{KUBELETCONFIG}}\n15\tparameters:\n16\t  - name: NAME\n17\t  - name: KUBELETCONFIG\n18\t    value: \"{}\"\n19\t  - name: POOL\n20\t    value: worker\n21\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01LvxZJ4Yutvn6tN8jjixSiJ","session_id":"b36bfe9c-b5ba-4115-8f21-75f99f58dba6","uuid":"717b3e03-e847-4b21-ae93-75b7685f4b60","timestamp":"2026-06-22T21:38:44.608Z","subagent_type":"Explore","task_description":"Find MachineConfigPool and KubeletConfig examples and best practices"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_013LQA69BhBxA85PripjAKwp","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# ADR-003: Node Update Lifecycle\n2\t\n3\t## Status\n4\tActive\n5\t\n6\t## Context\n7\tApplying config changes to nodes requires coordination between the cluster-level controller and the node-level daemon to avoid disrupting workloads.\n8\t\n9\t## Decision\n10\tUpdates follow a multi-phase lifecycle tracked by MachineConfigNode conditions:\n11\t\n12\t1. **Node Controller** detects config drift, respects `maxUnavailable`, sets target annotation\n13\t2. **MCD** picks up annotation change, cordons the node\n14\t3. **MCD** drains the node (evicts pods)\n15\t4. **MCD** applies config (files, systemd units, kernel args)\n16\t5. **MCD** performs OS update (rpm-ostree/bootc) if needed\n17\t6. **MCD** decides: reboot (OS/kernel changes) or service-reload (file-only changes)\n18\t7. **MCD** uncordons the node after successful apply\n19\t8. **Node Controller** updates pool status counters\n20\t\n21\tThe daemon reports granular progress via MachineConfigNode conditions (AppliedFiles, AppliedFilesAndOS, Drained, Cordoned, RebootedNode, ReloadedCRIO, etc.).\n22\t\n23\t## Consequences\n24\t- `maxUnavailable` on MachineConfigPool controls rollout speed\n25\t- Degraded nodes block pool progress (require manual intervention)\n26\t- Config drift monitoring detects unauthorized changes between updates\n27\t- Pausing a pool (`paused: true`) halts all updates to that pool\n28\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01FVjokv2fbL5yUVz4FEGkAj","session_id":"b36bfe9c-b5ba-4115-8f21-75f99f58dba6","uuid":"a0e223a0-f837-4295-a447-32cfc2df20b2","timestamp":"2026-06-22T21:38:44.609Z","subagent_type":"Explore","task_description":"Check project docs and AI docs for MCO conventions"}
