{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_011pEvxcrQDYqxuW9hARjx5j","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# MachineConfigController\n2\t\n3\t## Goals\n4\t\n5\t1. Coordinate upgrade of machines to desired configurations defined by a `MachineConfig` object.\n6\t\n7\t2. Provide options to control upgrade for `sets of machines` individually.\n8\t\n9\t## Non Goals\n10\t\n11\t1. MachineConfigController is not responsible for updating the machines directly.\n12\t\n13\t2. MachineConfigController is not responsible for serving Ignition configs to new machines trying to join the cluster.\n14\t\n15\t## Sub Controllers\n16\t\n17\t1. `TemplateController` is responsible for generating the MachineConfigs for pre-defined roles of machines from internal templates based on cluster configuration.\n18\t\n19\t2. `UpdateController` is responsible for upgrading machines to desired MachineConfig by coordinating with a daemon running on each machine.\n20\t\n21\t3. `RenderController` is responsible for discovering MachineConfigs for a `Pool of Machines` and generating the static MachineConfig.\n22\t\n23\t4. `KubeletConfigController` is responsible for wrapping custom Kubelet configurations within a CRD. The available options are documented within the KubeletConfiguration (https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/blob/release-1.11/pkg/kubelet/apis/kubeletconfig/v1beta1/types.go#L45).\n24\t\n25\t## MachineConfigPool\n26\t\n27\t```go\n28\ttype MachineConfigPool struct {\n29\t    metav1.TypeMeta `json:\",inline\"`\n30\t    metav1.ObjectMeta `json:\"metadata,omitempty\"`\n31\t\n32\t    Spec MachineConfigPoolSpec `json:\"spec\"`\n33\t    Status MachineConfigPoolStatus `json:\"status\"`\n34\t}\n35\t\n36\ttype MachineConfigPoolSpec struct {\n37\t    // Label selector for MachineConfigs.\n38\t    // Refer https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/overview/working-with-objects/labels/ on how label and selectors work.\n39\t    MachineConfigSelector *metav1.LabelSelector `json:\"machineConfigSelector,omitempty\"`\n40\t\n41\t    // Label selector for Machines.\n42\t    NodeSelector *metav1.LabelSelector `json:\"nodeSelector,omitempty\"`\n43\t\n44\t    // If true, changes to this machine config pool should be stopped.\n45\t    // This includes generating new desiredMachineConfig and update of machines.\n46\t    Paused bool `json:\"paused\"`\n47\t\n48\t    // MaxUnavailable defines either an integer number or percentage\n49\t    // of nodes in the pool that can go Unavailable during an update.\n50\t    // This includes nodes Unavailable for any reason, including user\n51\t    // initiated cordons, failing nodes, etc. The default value is 1.\n52\t    //\n53\t    // A value larger than 1 will mean multiple nodes going unavailable during\n54\t    // the update, which may affect your workload stress on the remaining nodes.\n55\t    // You cannot set this value to 0 to stop updates (it will default back to 1);\n56\t    // to stop updates, use the 'paused' property instead. Drain will respect\n57\t    // Pod Disruption Budgets (PDBs) such as etcd quorum guards, even if\n58\t    // MaxUnavailable is greater than one.\n59\t    MaxUnavailable *intstr.IntOrString `json:\"maxUnavailable\"`\n60\t}\n61\t\n62\ttype MachineConfigPoolStatus struct {\n63\t    // The generation observed by the controller.\n64\t    ObservedGeneration int64 `json:\"observedGeneration,omitempty\"`\n65\t\n66\t    // The current MachineConfig object for the machine config pool.\n67\t    CurrentMachineConfig string `json:\"currentMachineConfig\"`\n68\t\n69\t    // Total number of machines in the machine config pool.\n70\t    MachineCount int32 `json:\"machineCount\"`\n71\t\n72\t    // Total number of machines targeted by the pool that have the CurrentMachineConfig as their config.\n73\t    UpdatedMachineCount int32 `json:\"updatingMachines\"`\n74\t\n75\t    // Total number of ready machines targeted by the pool.\n76\t    ReadyMachineCount int32 `json:\"readyMachines\"`\n77\t\n78\t    // Total number of unavailable (non-ready) machines targeted by the pool.\n79\t    // A node is marked unavailable if it is in updating state or NodeReady condition is false.\n80\t    UnavailableMachineCount int32 `json:\"unavailableMachines\"`\n81\t\n82\t    // Represents the latest available observations of current state.\n83\t    Conditions []MachineConfigPoolConditions `json:\"conditions\"`\n84\t}\n85\t```\n86\t\n87\t## MachineSets vs MachineConfigPool\n88\t\n89\t- MachineSets describe nodes with respect to cloud / machine provider. MachineConfigPool allows MachineConfigController components to define and provide status of machines in context of upgrades.\n90\t\n91\t- MachineConfigPool also allows users to configure how upgrades are rolled out to the machines in a pool.\n92\t\n93\t- NodeSelector can be replaced with reference to MachineSet.\n94\t\n95\t## TemplateController\n96\t\n97\tThe TemplateController uses `internal templates` and a `configuration object` to generate OpenShift-owned MachineConfig objects for pre-defined `roles` like master, worker etc. These templates are stored in the `templates/` directory of this repository. For example, the `templates/master/00-master` directory will yield a MachineConfig object named `00-master` for the `master` role. Template variables such as `{{.EtcdCAData}}` are filled in using the controllerconfig custom resource (e.g. `controllerconfig/machine-config-controller`).\n98\t\n99\t- The TemplateController constantly reconciles the MachineConfig objects in the cluster to match its internal state (which is essentially: baked-in templates + controllerconfig). The TemplateController will overwrite any user changes of its owned objects.\n100\t\n101\t- TemplateController watches changes to the controllerconfig to generate OpenShift-owned MachineConfig objects.\n102\t\n103\t- TemplateController adds `OwnerReference` or similar annotations on its objects to declare ownership.\n104\t\n105\t## RenderController\n106\t\n107\tThe RenderController generates the desired MachineConfig object based on the MachineConfigSelector defined in MachineConfigPool.\n108\t\n109\t- RenderController watches for changes on MachineConfigPool object to find all the MachineConfig objects using `MachineConfigSelector` and updating the `CurrentMachineConfig` with the generated MachineConfig.\n110\t\n111\t- RenderController watches for changes on all the MachineConfig objects and syncs all the MachineConfigPool objects with new `CurrentMachineConfig`.\n112\t\n113\t### Finding MachineConfigs\n114\t\n115\tUse kubernetes Deployment behavior for LabelSelector to find Pods.\n116\t\n117\t### Generating desired MachineConfig\n118\t\n119\tUse the merging behavior defined in MachineConfig design document [here](./MachineConfig.md#how-to-create-generated-machineconfig) to create a single MachineConfig from all the MachineConfig objects that were selected above.\n120\t\n121\t#### Ordering the MachineConfigs\n122\t\n123\tThe render controller sorts all the other MachineConfigs based on the lexicographically increasing order of their `Name`. It uses the first MachineConfig in the list as the base and appends the rest to the base MachineConfig.\n124\t\n125\t## UpdateController\n126\t\n127\tThe UpdateController coordinates upgrade for machines in a MachineConfigPool. UpdateController uses annotations on node objects to coordinate with the `MachineConfigDaemon` running on each machine to upgrade each machine to the desired Machine Configuration.\n128\t\n129\tUpdateController watches for changes on MachineConfigPool and runs update if,\n130\t\n131\t1. If the `.Status.CurrentMachineConfig` has been updated.\n132\t\n133\t2. If new nodes can be updated to the current configuration as new Machines are available with old configuration if permitted by `NodeLimit` or the `NodeLimit` has increased allowing more nodes to be updated.\n134\t\n135\t**Historically** the following annotations were used to coordinate between UpdateController and the MachineConfigDaemon,\n136\t\n137\t- node-configuration.v1.coreos.com/currentConfig\n138\t- node-configuration.v1.coreos.com/targetConfig\n139\t- node-configuration.v1.coreos.com/desiredConfig\n140\t\n141\tWith these three fields it becomes possible to determine the update progress of the machine:\n142\t\n143\t- desiredConfig == currentConfig: The machine is up-to-date.\n144\t- desiredConfig != currentConfig && desiredConfig == targetConfig: The machine is not up-to-date, but is in the process of updating.\n145\t- desiredConfig != currentConfig && desiredConfig != targetConfig: The machine is not up-to-date and is not in the process of updating.\n146\t- Node is marked updated by UpdateController unless `NodeReady` is reported by kubelet.\n147\t\n148\t## UpdateController interface with MachineConfigDaemon\n149\t\n150\tFollowing annotations on node object will be used by UpdateController to coordinate node update with MachineConfigDaemon.\n151\t\n152\t- machine-config-daemon.v1.openshift.com/currentConfig : defines the current MachineConfig applied by MachineConfigDaemon.\n153\t- machine-config-daemon.v1.openshift.com/desiredConfig : defines the desired MachineConfig that need to be applied by MachineConfigDaemon\n154\t- machine-config-daemon.v1.openshift.com/state : defines the state of the MachineConfigDaemon, It can be done, working and degraded.\n155\t\n156\tWith these three fields it becomes possible to determine the update progress of the machine:\n157\t\n158\t  a. desiredConfig == currentConfig : The machine is up-to-date.\n159\t\n160\t  b. desiredConfig != currentConfig && state == working : The machine is not up-to-date, but is in the process of updating.\n161\t\n162\t  c. desiredConfig != currentConfig && state == degraded : The machine is not up-to-date and MachineConfigDaemon cannot apply the desired configuration.\n163\t\n164\tNode is marked updated by UpdateController only when `NodeReady` is reported by kubelet when case (a) is true.\n165\t\n166\t## KubeletConfig\n167\t\n168\tThe KubeletConfigController manages the KubeletConfig CRD allowing customers to manage their Feature Flags, Max Pods, and other Kubelet options.\n169\t\n170\tThe `KubeletConfigController` listens for changes within KubeletConfig CRDs and merges in changes from the user.\n171\t\n172\tWhen the user creates a new KubeletConfig object they pass in the MachineConfigPoolSelector to target.\n173\t\n174\tThe MachineConfigController performs the following operations:\n175\t\n176\t1. Validates the user defined KubeletConfig\n177\t1. Renders the current MachineConfig (storage.files.contents[kubelet.conf]) into the KubeletConfiguration structure\n178\t1. Loads the user's KubeletConfig instance\n179\t1. Uses mergo to merge the two structures\n180\t1. Serializes the KubeletConfig to json\n181\t1. Creates or Updates a MachineConfig (called `99-[role]-kubelet-managed`) with a new /etc/kubernetes/kubelet.conf\n182\t\n183\tThe machine will subsequently reboot by the MachineConfigDaemon to apply the new config.\n184\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_vrtx_01FVjokv2fbL5yUVz4FEGkAj","session_id":"b36bfe9c-b5ba-4115-8f21-75f99f58dba6","uuid":"17c7c9f1-3444-4bd2-a7a1-60a8687cd3ae","timestamp":"2026-06-22T21:38:55.869Z","subagent_type":"Explore","task_description":"Check project docs and AI docs for MCO conventions"}
